17":"1317","Chilton, Suffolk, England":"Chilton, Suffolk, England, United Kingdom","Saint Gregory's, Sudbury, England":"Sudbury, Suffolk, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Butler","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: from a word that originally denoted a wine steward, usually the chief servant of a medieval household, from Norman French <i>butuiller</i> (Old French <i>bouteillier</i>, Latin <i>buticularius</i>, from <i>buticula</i> ‘bottle’). In the large households of royalty and the most powerful nobility, the title came to denote an officer of high rank and responsibility, only nominally concerned with the supply of wine, if at all. As well as being widespread in England, this is also the surname of an important Irish family, descended from Theobald FitzWalter, who was appointed Chief Butler of Ireland by King Henry II in 1177. It is Gaelicized as <i>de Buitléir</i>.","English: occasionally perhaps an occupational name from Middle English <i>boteler</i> ‘maker of bottles (usually of leather)’, a derivative of Middle English <i>botel</i>, Old French <i>bo(u)teille</i> ‘bottle’ and synonymous with <i>Botelmaker</i>.","Americanized form of French   Bouthillier   (see   Bouteiller  )."],"variants":[{"name":"Buttler","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): variant of   Butler  .","German: occupational name for a village tavern owner, from French <i>bouteillier</i> ‘butler’.","Americanized form of German <b>Buttlar</b>: habitational name from a place so named in Thuringia."]},{"name":"Bouthillier","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Andre, Armand, Jacques, Normand, Philippe, Yves.","French: variant of   Bouteiller  . This name is sometimes Americanized as   Butler  . Compare   Boutilier  ."]}]},{"name":"Andreus","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["The original New Testament Greek form of   Andrew  , used in the English-speaking world as a learned variant."],"variants":[{"name":"Andries","meanings":["form of the Greek name <i>Andreas</i>, a short form of any of various compound names derived from <i>andr-</i> ‘man, warrior’. In the New Testament this is the name of the first disciple to be called by Jesus. After the Resurrection,  St Andrew  preached in Asia Minor and Greece. He is traditionally believed to have been crucified at Patras in Achaia. He was one of the most popular saints of the Middle Ages and was adopted as the patron of Scotland, Russia, and Greece. It has long been among the most popular boys' names in the English-speaking world, especially in Scotland. Its popularity in England was further enhanced by its use as a British royal name for  Prince Andrew  (  b. 1960 ), the Duke of York."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Andreus Butler was born before 1370, his father, Thomas Boteler, was 52 and his mother, Margaret Adelby, was 52. He married Catherine Carbonel in 1373, in Chilton, Suffolk, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 daughter. He died about 1429, and was buried in Sudbury, Suffolk, England, United Kingdom."},"et":{"before 1370–about 1429":"enne 1370–umbes 1429","1370–1429":"1370–1429","1370–Female":"1370–Surnud","1390–Female":"1390–Surnud","1317–1393":"1317–1393","1318–Female":"1318–Surnud","about 1429":"umbes 1429","after 1393":"pärast 1393","1373":"1373","before 1370":"enne 1370","1393":"1393","1370":"1370","Bef 1390":"enne 1390","1429":"1429","1318":"1318","1390":"1390","1317":"1317","Chilton, Suffolk, England":"Chilton, Suffolk, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Saint Gregory's, Sudbury, England":"Sudbury, Suffolk, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"before 1370–about 1429":"ennen vuotta 1370–noin 1429","1370–1429":"1370–1429","1370–Female":"1370–Kuollut","1390–Female":"1390–Kuollut","1317–1393":"1317–1393","1318–Female":"1318–Kuollut","about 1429":"noin 1429","after 1393":"1393 jälkeen","1373":"1373